Source code and binary executables for Linux, OSX, and Windows are freely available under a permissive BSD license: https://bitbucket.org/dkessner/forqs Contact: jnovembre@uchicago.edu, dkessner@ucla.edu 1 Introduction Simulations have a long history in population genetics, both for verifying ana- lytical results and for exploring population models that are mathematically in- tractable.

Binary executables can be obtained for Linux, OSX, and Windows from: https://bitbucket.org/dkessner/forqs/downloads About the image The image on the rst page was created based on haplotype frequency infor- mation reported during a forqs simulation.

The latest forqs packages are available here: https://bitbucket.org/dkessner/forqs/downloads forqs is a command line program that takes a single argument specifying the conguration le for the simulation: forqs config_file Theforqs packages include an examples directory containing several exam- ple conguration les.

The code can be obtained via git from bitbucket: git clone https://bitbucket.org/dkessner/forqs.git If you have the both the Boost libraries and the Boost build system installed, you can build forqs with the bjam tool, which is the Boost build system's equivalent of make : cd forqs/src bjam 8.2 Structure of the codebase Most code units in the forqs project consist of three les: interface (header le) implementation (cpp le) unit test (cpp le) For example, the code for the Locus module can be found in the les Locus.hpp ,Locus.cpp ,LocusTest.cpp .

One can generate an overlay for any set  downloaded from Scopus as follows:    ÔÇ∑       Search in Scopus (advanced or basic); for example, using the search string  ‚ÄòTITLE( ‚Äúhumanities computing‚Äù ) OR TI TLE( ‚Äúcomputational humanities‚Äù ) OR  TITLE( ‚Äúdigital humanities‚Äù ) OR TITLE( ‚Äúehumanities‚Äù ) OR TITLE( ‚Äúe-humanities‚Äù )‚Äô  provided 114 documents on October 8, 2013;   ÔÇ∑       Make a possible selection of records among the retrieved documents or tick ‚ÄúAll‚Äù;   ÔÇ∑       Click on ‚ÄúExport‚Äù;   ÔÇ∑       Among the output formats, choose the ‚ÄúRIS format (Reference Manager, Procite,  Endnote)‚Äù and ‚ÄúSpecify fields to be exported‚Äù;   ÔÇ∑       Only ‚ÄúSource titles‚Äù should be exported; untick all other fields;   ÔÇ∑       Click on ‚ÄúExport‚Äù: the file ‚Äúscopus.ris‚Äù can be saved; for example, for the 114 records  mentioned  at http://www.leydesdorff.net/scopus_ovl/scopus.ris ;  ÔÇ∑       Save the file ‚Äúscopus.ris‚Äù in the same folder as the routine overlay.exe  (at  http://www.leydesdorff.net/scopus_ovl /overlay.exe ) and the file with the mapping  information scopus.dbf  (at http://www.leydesdorff.net/scopus_ovl/scopus.dbf ; right -click  for saving this file).

ÔÇ∑       One can now run overlay.exe in that same folder; preferabl y from the C -prompt; (using  the C -prompt, one obtains error messages);   ÔÇ∑       The file ‚Äú overlay.txt ‚Äù (e.g., ehum.txt ; at http://w ww.leydesdorff.net/scopus_ovl/ehum.txt   ) is a map file that can be opened in VOSviewer  (available at http://www.vosviewer.com   );   ÔÇ∑       Rao-Stirling diversity is stored in  the file ‚Äúrao.txt‚Äù in the same folder, and shown on the  screen; overlay.dbf contains the information such as the number of publications in each  journal.
